{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Argobba |image = | population = 140,134 (2007 census)<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/pdf/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf "Census 2007"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305000000/http://www.csa.gov.et/pdf/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf |date=March 5, 2009 }}, first draft, Table 5.</ref> |popplace = [[Ethiopia]] |languages = [[Argobba language|Argobba]], [[Oromo language|Oromo]], [[Amharic language|Amharic]], [[Harari language|Harari]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]], and [[Saho-Afar languages|Saho-Afar]] |rels=[[Sunni Islam]] |related-c = [[Amhara people|Amhara]], [[Harari people|Harari]], [[Gurage]], [[Oromo people|Oromo]], [[Somali people|Somali]], [[Tigray-Tigrinya people|Tigray]], [[Tigre people|Tigre]] and other [[Cushitic|Cushitic peoples]]. }} The '''Argobba''' are an ethnic group inhabiting [[Ethiopia]]. A [[Islam in Ethiopia|Muslim]] community, they are spread out through isolated village networks and towns in the northeastern and eastern parts of the country. Group members have typically been astute traders and merchants, and have adjusted to the economic trends in their area. These factors have led to a decline in usage of the [[Argobba language]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Argobba of Ethiopia|url=http://joshuaproject.net/people-profile.php?peo3=10422&rog3=ET|work=Ethnic people profile|publisher=Joshua Project|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=Zelealem>[http://www.sil.org/silesr/2002/026/SILESR2002-026.pdf Leyew, Zelealem and Ralph Siebert. (2001) "Sociolinguistic survey report of the Argobba language of Ethiopia"], SIL International (accessed 25 May 2009)</ref>
==Distribution== Argobba communities can be found in the [[Afar Region|Afar]], [[Harari Region|Harari]], [[Amhara Region|Amhara]], and [[Oromia Region|Oromia]] Regions, in and along the [[Great Rift Valley, Ethiopia|Great Rift Valley]]. They include Yimlawo, Gusa, [[Shonke]], [[Berehet]], Khayr Amba, Melka Jilo, [[Aliyu Amba]], [[Metehara]], [[Shewa Robit]], and the surrounding rural villages.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=agj "Argobba: A language of Ethiopia"], Ethnologue website (accessed 25 May 2009)</ref>
==Language== The Argobba traditionally speak the [[Argobba language]], an [[Afro-Asiatic language]] of the [[Semitic language|Semitic]] branch. In some places, Argobba has homogenized with [[Oromo language|Oromo]]. In other areas, the people have shifted to neighboring languages for economic reasons. At this time there are only a few areas left where the Argobba are not at least bilingual in Amharic, [[Oromo language|Oromiffa]] or [[Afar language|Afar]]. All of these languages have a literature that can be used to serve the Argobba, even though their current literacy rate in any language is low; the Argobba reportedly do not like to send their children to school and do not go to court.<ref name=Zelealem/>{{dead link|date=October 2018}}
==See also== * [[Argobba special woreda (Afar)|Argobba special woreda]] in the Afar Regon * [[Argobba special woreda (Amhara)|Argobba special woreda]] in the Amhara Regon * [[Argoba Nationality Democratic Organization]]
