'''William Lee "Billy" Wilbanks''' (May 30, 1940 - October 9, 2018) was an American criminologist and former professor of criminal justice at [[Florida International University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dossmanfh.com/obituary/william-wilbanks-phd|title=Obituary for William L. "Billy" Wilbanks, Ph.D. at Dossman Funeral Home|website=www.dossmanfh.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref><ref name=about/><ref name=sentinel>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1986-10-29/news/8603060415_1_jury-report-grand-jury-prentice-rasheed |title=Merchant Free In Booby-trap Death |last=Thompson |first=Jean |website=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |publication-date=29 October 1986}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-08-18/news/mn-1460_1_jesse-james-days/2 |title='We're Back to the Jesse James Days': Miami Plagued by Expressway Bandits |last=Bearak |first=Barry |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publication-date=18 August 1985}}</ref>
==Education== Wilbanks graduated from [[Belton High School (Belton, Texas)|Belton High School]] in [[Belton, Texas]] in 1958. At Belton High, he was an all-state guard on the State AA Championship basketball team that won the Class 2A championship in 1958.<ref name="about">{{Cite web |url=http://www.texastrackchamps.com/about.html |title=About William Wilbanks |website=William Wilbanks' Personal Website}}</ref><ref name=tdt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tdtnews.com/archive/article_2ecb17b2-da33-52ff-a673-738c73554683.html |title=Belton to unveil wall of honor |last=Rajan |first=Greg |website=[[Temple Daily Telegram]] |publication-date=28 September 2001}}</ref> He went on to receive his B.A. from [[Abilene Christian College]] in 1963, after which he received his M.A.'s from Abilene Christian College, [[Sam Houston State University]], and the [[University at Albany, SUNY]] in 1965, 1972, and 1972, respectively. In 1975, he received his Ph.D. in criminal justice from University at Albany, SUNY.<ref name=about/> ==Career== Wilbanks taught at Florida International University from 1973 to 1999, and has written over 20 books and 70 journal articles.<ref name=about/><ref name=ttu/> In 2001, he returned to Belton to build the Belton High School Athletic Wall of Honor, which honors 72 of the school's athletes and five of its championship teams.<ref name=tdt/><ref name=ttu>{{Cite web |url=https://www.depts.ttu.edu/english/general_info/awards_financial_aid/undergrad_scholarships_and_awards/tech_comm_awards/wilbanks_scholarship.php |title=William Wilbanks Technical Communication Scholarship |website=Department of English |publisher=[[Texas Tech University]]}}</ref> [[Texas Tech University]]'s Department of English awards the William Wilbanks Technical Communication Scholarship to some of its undergraduates who are [[technical communication]] majors, and who have GPAs of 3.0 or higher.<ref name=ttu/> ==Media appearances== From 1981 to 1997, Wilbanks appeared on television over 30 times as a criminology expert.<ref name=about/> These appearances included four on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Crossfire (U.S. TV program)|Crossfire]]'' and two on [[CBS]]' ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.shsu.edu/~pin_www/T@S/2001/Wilbanks.html |title=Presentation To Feature Stories About Police Women Killed in Duty |website=SHSU News |publisher=[[Sam Houston State University]] |publication-date=25 January 2001}}</ref> He appeared on multiple televised debates in which he argued that [[Prentice Rasheed]], a shopkeeper in Dade County, Florida, should be indicted for setting a booby trap that killed a suspected burglar. Despite this, Rasheed was not indicted by the grand jury.<ref name=sentinel/> After the jury made this decision, Wilbanks said, "People are thinking, if the police don't do the job, then I can do whatever I want. That's bad news. I don't think any of us wants to live in a booby-trapped society. A trap can't discriminate between a burglar, a fireman, a policeman or the Amway lady."<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-14/news/mn-29468_1_booby-trap/3 |title=Booby Trap Debate: Protecting Property--What Price? |last=Bearak |first=Barry |website=Los Angeles Times |page=3 |publication-date=14 November 1986}}</ref>
